---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Mermaid from '../../../components/Mermaid.astro';
---
<DocsLayout title="5-layer pipeline" slug="architecture/pipeline" description="From brief to validated output — the five layers of a Skill Wiki turn.">
  <h1>5-layer pipeline</h1>
  <p style="color: var(--fg-muted);">
    A turn through Skill Wiki has exactly five layers. Three are protocol (frozen at v1);
    two are pluggable (domain-defined).
  </p>

  <h2>The pipeline</h2>
  <p><img src="/architecture-system.png" alt="Skill Wiki system architecture — 8 layers from entry to model providers" /></p>

  <p>
    The architecture image above shows the full surface (8 horizontal bands). Within
    a single agent turn, the data path is:
  </p>

  <Mermaid>{`flowchart TD
    Brief["Brief (free text)"]
    Intent["IntentObject<br/><i>domain-defined shape</i>"]
    Ranked["ranked atom set"]
    Contracted["contracted atom set + projections"]
    Artifact["artifact (HTML / JSON / prose)"]
    Verdict["verdict { ok | fix-instructions }"]

    Brief -->|"L1 — Intent classification (plugin)"| Intent
    Intent -->|"L2 — Retrieval (protocol)"| Ranked
    Ranked -->|"L3 — Composition (protocol)"| Contracted
    Contracted -->|"L4 — Generation (agent)"| Artifact
    Artifact -->|"L5 — Validation (plugin)"| Verdict`}</Mermaid>

  <h2>Layer-by-layer</h2>

  <h3>L1 · Intent classification (plugin)</h3>
  <p>
    Free-text brief in. <code>IntentObject</code> out. The shape is
    <em>domain-defined</em> — Skill Wiki only specifies that L1 must produce a
    serialisable object that downstream layers can read.
  </p>
<pre><code>{`// Example (security domain)
interface SecurityIntentObject {
  task_type: "threat-model" | "compliance-check" | "code-review";
  target_surface: "api-endpoint" | "auth-flow" | "data-pipeline";
  severity_threshold: "low" | "medium" | "high" | "critical";
  required_frameworks: string[];
  ambiguity_flags: string[];
}`}</code></pre>

  <h3>L2 · Retrieval (protocol)</h3>
  <p>
    <code>IntentObject</code> + corpus index in. Ranked atom set out. The reference
    implementation uses <strong>6-axis ranking</strong>: kind match, tag match, edge
    centrality, projection-fit cost, persona affinity, validator quality. The protocol
    only specifies that L2 returns an ordered list of atom ids with explanations.
  </p>

  <h3>L3 · Composition (protocol)</h3>
  <p>
    Ranked atoms + their contracts in. A "contracted set" out — atoms whose contracts
    have been resolved (must-includes pulled in, must-avoids filtered, conditionals
    evaluated against the IntentObject). The projection level for each atom is also
    decided here based on the budget.
  </p>

  <h3>L4 · Generation (agent)</h3>
  <p>
    The agent itself is L4. Given the contracted atom set + their loaded projections,
    the agent generates the final artifact. Skill Wiki has nothing to say about
    <em>how</em> the agent generates — only about what's in its context when it does.
  </p>

  <h3>L5 · Validation (plugin)</h3>
  <p>
    Generated artifact + corpus rules in. Verdict out. The shape is
    <em>domain-defined</em>: HTML structure validation, JSON-schema check, regex over
    prose, LLM-judge over a rubric — all valid implementations of L5. Failures
    surface fix instructions; up to two retry cycles before hard-failing.
  </p>

  <h2>Why "L5" and not "L4"?</h2>
  <p>
    L1, L2, L3 are <em>compile-time validators</em> in name (parser → semantic →
    cross-atom). L4 is the agent. L5 is the <em>runtime output</em> validator. The
    naming is consistent — every L-prefix is "validation layer N." Generation has no
    L-number.
  </p>

  <h2>What's frozen vs what's free</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Layer</th><th>Frozen at v1?</th><th>Variability</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>L1 — Intent</td><td>No (plugin)</td><td>Object shape per domain.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>L2 — Retrieval</td><td>Yes (interface)</td><td>Ranking algo can vary.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>L3 — Composition</td><td>Yes</td><td>Contract evaluation is deterministic.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>L4 — Generation</td><td>—</td><td>Agent's job; not part of protocol.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>L5 — Validation</td><td>No (plugin)</td><td>Validator shape per domain.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    See <a href="/docs/architecture/compile-time">Compile time</a> and
    <a href="/docs/architecture/runtime">Runtime</a> for how L2 + L3 + L5 are
    implemented in the reference v0.1.0.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
